				\begin{document}$$\propto {n,p}$$\end{document}) with interface and mid-gap states14. Weak electron-phonon coupling and phonon-phonon scattering42 slows carrier thermalization and intraband relaxation, instead stabilizing the hot carriers and resulting in prolonged decay times. In addition, for Δ>Δplt\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\Delta >\Delta _{plt}$$\end{document} at temperatures ≥200\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\ge 200$$\end{document} K, hh3-e1 transitions are symmetrically excited at k⊥>0\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$k_{\perp }>0$$\end{document}, where local minima in the hh3 states are suspected to further stabilize the holes and even reduce charge separation by reducing wavefunction overlap. During the plateau regime, scattering to k=0\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$k=0$$\end{document} states is further reduced and conventional Auger scattering (∝n2p,np2\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\propto {n^{2}}p,np^{2}$$\end{document}) occurs, pushing carriers deep into their respective bands. In InAs, Auger scattering is dominant for holes32–34. Slowly, the carrier density decreases via intra-valence band scattering and the dynamics revert to that seen for excitation Δ>Δplt\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\Delta >\Delta _{plt}$$\end{document}.

In conclusion, excited metastable carriers can be observed when the excess photon energy exceeds ∼\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\sim$$\end{document} 100 meV at sufficiently low lattice temperature. This metastability most likely corresponds to local minima in the non-zero in-plane wavevector states of the hh3 band and leads to an accumulation of carriers that have a slow intra-valence cooling. The dynamics of the meta-stable states are dominated by Auger scattering that can potentially increase hot-carrier extraction, assuming that extraction can be achieved faster than the cooling. Once intra-valence band scattering occurs the electron and hole recombination rates are typically slow due to charge-carrier separation in the MQW structure and a slow cooling mechanism due to phonon-phonon coupling limits and a thermal conductivity mismatch in the structure. Hence, the long-lived carrier lifetimes that are already suitable for hot-carrier extraction in solar cells could be further enhanced by making use of the metastable state at early times. Moreover, this metastability is likely to be present in all narrow-well InAs/AlAsSb MQW systems. Dynamics from this work can be applied to device-like systems where electricity extraction can also be affected by tunnelling between the wells16.

